{{Politics of Bhutan}}
The '''Dratshang Lhentshog''' ([[Dzongkha]]: {{big|གྲྭ་ཚང་ལྷན་ཚོགས་}}; [[Wylie transliteration|Wylie]]: ''grwa-tshang lhan-tshogs'') is the Commission for the Monastic Affairs of [[Bhutan]].<ref name=CoBE-gloss>{{cite web |url=http://www.constitution.bt/TsaThrim%20Eng%20(A5).pdf |format=PDF |title=Constitution of the Kingdom of Bhutan (English) – Glossary |publisher=Government of Bhutan |date=2008-07-18 |accessdate=2010-10-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162637/http://www.constitution.bt/TsaThrim%20Eng%20%28A5%29.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-06 |df= }}</ref> Under the [[Constitution of Bhutan|2008 Constitution]], it is the bureaucracy that oversees the [[Drukpa Kagyu]] sect that is the [[state religion]] of Bhutan. Although Bhutan has a state religion, the role of the religious bureaucracy ideally complements secular institutions within a [[dual system of government]].
==Composition and Function== Under the [[Constitution of Bhutan|2008 Constitution]], the Dratshang Lhentshog is made up of seven members: the [[Je Khenpo]] as Chairman; the Five Lopons ([[Dzongkha]]: སློབ་དཔོན་ལྔ་; [[Wylie transliteration|Wylie]]: ''slob-dpon lnga'') of the Zhung Dratshang ([[Dzongkha]]: གཞུང་གྲྭ་ཚང་; [[Wylie transliteration|Wylie]]: ''gzhung grwa-tshang''; "Central Monastic Body"<ref name=CoBE-gloss/>); and a civil servant Secretary.<ref name=CoBE-3>{{cite web |url=http://www.constitution.bt/TsaThrim%20Eng%20(A5).pdf |format=PDF |title=Constitution of the Kingdom of Bhutan (English) – Article 3 |publisher=Government of Bhutan |date=2008-07-18 |accessdate=2010-12-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162637/http://www.constitution.bt/TsaThrim%20Eng%20%28A5%29.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-06 |df= }}</ref> Under the 2008 Constitution, it is mandated that the Zhung Dratshang and ''rabdeys'' (monastic bodies in [[dzong]]s other than [[Punakha]] and [[Thimphu]])<ref name=CoBE-gloss/> receive state funding and facilities adequate to support the [[Drukpa Kagyu]] sect.<ref name=CoBE-3/>
The Five Lopons recommend a learned and respected monk ordained in accordance with the [[Drukpa Lineage|Druk-lu]], having the nine qualities of a spiritual master, and being accomplished in ''ked-dzog'' (spiritual development and completion),<ref name=DWBDict>{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondway-buddhism.org/diction/diction.htm |title=Tibetan-English-Dictionary of Buddhist Teaching & Practice |publisher=Rangjung Yeshe Translations & Publications |work=Diamond Way Buddhism Worldwide |year=1996 |accessdate=2010-12-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328014624/http://www.diamondway-buddhism.org/diction/diction.htm |archivedate=2010-03-28 |df= }}</ref> to the [[Druk Gyalpo|King of Bhutan]]. The King then appoints that monk to the office of [[Je Khenpo]].<ref name=CoBE-3/> In turn, the Lopons are appointed on the same criteria by the Je Khenpo on the advice of the remaining members of the Dratshang Lhentshog.<ref name=CoBE-3/>
The sitting [[Je Khenpo]] is the formal leader of the southern branch of the [[Drukpa Kagyu]] sect, which is part of the [[Kagyu]] tradition of [[Tibetan Buddhism|Himalayan Buddhism]]. The primary duty of the Je Khenpo is to lead the Dratshang Lhentshog and to arbitrate on matters of doctrine, assisted by the Five Lopons.<ref name=USLCCS2>{{cite book|last1=Worden |first1=Robert L. |last2=Savada |first2=Andrea Matles (ed.) |title=Nepal and Bhutan: Country Studies |chapter=Chapter 6 - Bhutan: Religious Tradition |edition=3rd |year=1991 |publisher=Federal Research Division, [[United States Library of Congress]] |isbn=0-8444-0777-1 |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/bttoc.html |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> The Je Khenpo is also responsible for many important liturgical and religious duties across the country. Aside from the [[Druk Gyalpo|King of Bhutan]], only the Je Khenpo may don a saffron [[kabney]].<ref name=USLCCS3>{{cite book|last1=Worden |first1=Robert L. |last2=Savada |first2=Andrea Matles (ed.) |title=Nepal and Bhutan: Country Studies |chapter=Chapter 6 - Bhutan: Social System |edition=3rd |year=1991 |publisher=Federal Research Division, [[United States Library of Congress]] |isbn=0-8444-0777-1 |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/bttoc.html |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>
